# ADR 0001: Practice of using ADRs

## Status
Accepted (date: 2026-05-14)

## Context
The Company is building a new claims management system using azure and node.js and will take many technical decisions over the upcoming weeks
Without having a record, decisions get forgotten, re-litigated or misunderstood by the new team members joining the team 
And We also don't know how large the team and how fast the team will grow.

## Decision
We will use architectural diagram to capture every technical decision made in the making of the system.
Every ADR follows the same format: Status, Context, Decision, Consequences, Alternatives
Any decision thats gonna affect the system design, architecture, or workflow needs a individual ADR.


## Consequences
- Easier
The new team members can understand why the system is built the way it is 
Revisiting past details have a paper trail
Dissagreements can be resolved by writing down instead of arguing

- Harder
Every significant decision requires a short write-up before merging — adds a small upfront cost
The team must agree on what counts as "significant enough" to warrant an ADR

- Different
Technical discussions now produce a written artefact, not just a Slack thread
The codebase becomes self-documenting at the architectural level

## Alternatives considered
- Relying on PR Desicions - rejected because PR descriptions are scattered, hard to search, and don't capture the why behind a decision in a structured way.
